### Write the final email
</Markdown>
<TextArea id="final_email" rows="10" />
</Vertical>

<Vertical id="tab2" title="Krish's Outline">
<Markdown>
1. _Why Sierra's Sister Shouldn't Give Up On the Clean-Up Routine._

   Don't give up on the clean-up routine yet -- I really think we can turn this around! Consistent expectations are one of the most reliable things for a six-year-old: better behavior, fewer power struggles, more security. The plan isn't broken; we just need to adjust the approach until we find what works.
</Markdown>
<Markdown>
2. _What psychological technique we are recommending._

    To encourage a child to clean up when asked, it's a great idea
    to use positive reinforcement.

3. _Explanation of what positive reinforcement is and why it works._

    Instead of focusing on what the child is doing wrong, positive
    reinforcement highlights and rewards good behavior, making it
    more likely to happen again in the future.

    Positive reinforcement is effective because it strengthens the
    behavior you want to see. Instead of focusing on what the child
    might do "wrong," this method encourages compliance and cooperation
    by creating positive associations with cleaning up. Children are more
    likely to repeat behaviors that earn them rewards and praise, and
    they feel more motivated when they know their actions are recognized
    in a positive way.

4. _List of positive reinforcement techniques she can use to try to get Logan to clean up his toys._

    **Sticker Chart**: Reward each clean-up with a sticker to
    track progress visually.

    **Story Time**: Offer a favorite story as a reward for
    putting toys away when asked.

    **Special Toy Bin**: Let them choose a fun, colorful bin to
    put their toys away in.

    **Extra Playtime**: Reward with a few minutes of extra playtime
    for their efforts.

5. _Final paragraph -- wish her luck!_

   I hope with this advice, things go much more smoothly with Logan.
</Markdown>
</Vertical>

<Vertical id="tab3" title="Lin's Outline">
<Markdown>
1. _Why Sierra's Sister Shouldn't Give Up On the Clean-Up Routine._

   I'd encourage you not to abandon consistent expectations around cleaning up. Predictable routines are strongly linked to healthy behavior in young children, and removing that structure usually makes things harder, not easier. The trouble so far isn't a sign that clean-up routines don't work -- it's a sign the strategy needs adjusting.
</Markdown>
<Markdown>
2. _What psychological technique we are recommending._

   Using positive reinforcement is an effective way to encourage a child
   to clean up when asked.

3. _Explanation of what positive reinforcement is and why it works._

   Positive reinforcement involves rewarding the child when they perform
   the desired behavior, which increases the likelihood that they will
   repeat it in the future.

   It helps establish a clear connection between the desired behavior
   (cleaning up when asked) and the rewarding outcome. This approach
   encourages the child to view cleaning up as a positive experience rather
   than something to resist, fostering motivation and cooperation over
   time. By focusing on rewarding good behavior rather than punishing
   noncompliance, the child is more likely to feel empowered and develop
   healthy habits.

4. _List of positive reinforcement techniques she can use to try to get Logan to clean up his toys._

   **Clean-Up Song**: Sing a fun clean-up song together while they put
   their toys away.

   **Golden Star Award**: Create a "Golden Star" award for being a
   great clean-up helper.

   **Helper of the Day**: Let them wear a fun "Helper of the Day" badge
   when they tidy up.

   **Countdown Timer**: Use a timer with a cheerful tune to make cleaning up
   feel like a game.

   **Healthy Snack**: Reward with a small, healthy snack like fruit or
   yogurt after the toys are away.

5.  _Final paragraph -- wish her luck!_

    With luck, this will help!
</Markdown>
</Vertical>

<Vertical id="tab4" title="Sierra's Outline">
<Markdown>
1. _Why Sierra's Sister Shouldn't Give Up On the Clean-Up Routine._

   Okay, so I know it feels like nothing's working, but please don't give up on the clean-up routine. Every kid I've been around does better with a routine they can count on -- it's easier on everybody once it clicks. The routine isn't the problem; we just haven't found the thing that works for him yet.
</Markdown>
<Markdown>
2. _What psychological technique we are recommending._

   Positive reinforcement is a powerful strategy to encourage desired
   behaviors in children, such as cleaning up when asked.

3. _Explanation of what positive reinforcement is and why it works._

   Positive reinforcement involves providing a desirable reward or
   incentive after the desired behavior occurs, increasing the likelihood
   that the behavior will be repeated.

   It is effective because it motivates behavior through encouragement
   rather than conflict. Children are more likely to cooperate when they
   know their efforts will be recognized and appreciated. Additionally,
   it helps build their sense of accomplishment and strengthens their
   ability to follow routines, which is crucial for their development.
   By using positive reinforcement, you create a routine that feels
   rewarding and enjoyable for the child, making it easier for them
   to develop healthy habits over time.


4. _List of positive reinforcement techniques she can use to try to get Logan to clean up his toys._

    **Clean-Up Buddy**: Let them pick a favorite stuffed animal to
    "help" put the toys away.

    **Favorite Song**: Play one favorite song to dance to once all
    the toys are put away.

    **Superhero Role**: Call them a "clean-up superhero" for helping achieve
    their goals.

    **Magical Clean-Up Passport**: Stamp their passport every time
    they put their toys away.

    **Choose the Next Activity**: Let them choose the next fun activity
    once clean-up is done

5.  _Final paragraph -- wish her luck!_

    I hope these techniques make clean-up time with Logan a lot easier!
</Markdown>
</Vertical>

